Reasoning: The solution passed all provided sample tests and extensive randomized brute-force checks (I ran the samples and random small tests up to length 12, deterministic edge cases, and a larger test of 20 '?' and all outputs matched expected results), so functionally it is correct. The code is readable with helpful comments explaining the DP state and transitions, but lacks detailed docstrings and could be slightly more polished. Algorithmically it is straightforward and correct, however it uses a full O(n^2) 2D DP table in Python instead of a space-optimized rolling array which would be more concise and memory-friendly. Because of that large memory footprint for n up to 3000, it may risk MLE on tight-memory judges, reducing robustness.
